  "prompt": "What is the structure of a microscope and its functions?",
  "response": "A microscope is an optical instrument used to view objects that are too small to be seen by the naked eye. Here's a breakdown of its structure and functions:\n\nMain Structural Components:\n\n1. Optical System:\n- Objective lens: Closest to the specimen, provides initial magnification\n- Eyepiece (ocular) lens: Located at the top, further magnifies the image\n- Tube: Connects objective and eyepiece lenses\n\n2. Mechanical System:\n- Stage: Flat platform where specimens are placed\n- Stage clips: Hold slides in place\n- Focusing knobs: Fine and coarse adjustment for clear image\n- Illumination system: Light source beneath the stage\n\n3. Base:\n- Supports the entire microscope\n- Contains light source\n- Provides stability\n\n4. Additional Components:\n- Condenser: Concentrates and focuses light\n- Diaphragm/iris: Controls light intensity\n- Arm: Connects base to optical tube\n\nFunctions:\n\n1. Magnification:\n- Produces enlarged images of small specimens\n- Typically ranges from 40x to 1000x\n\n2. Resolution:\n- Provides clear, detailed images\n- Distinguishes between closely spaced objects\n\n3. Observation:\n- Examines microorganisms, cells, tissues, and small structures\n\nDifferent types include compound, stereo, electron, and digital microscopes.",
